summary:
Myometrial electrical activity, measured through electrohysterography, is currently considered experimental rather than clinically validated for identifying preterm labor due to lack of integration into established diagnostic protocols. The existing literature supports reliance instead on proven methods such as cervical length assessment, tocolytic monitoring, and fetal fibronectin testing—none of which involve direct measurement of myometrial electric signals.\boxed{B}

The summary should end with an explicitly stated answer choice within boxed{}.

Myometrial electrical activity detected by electrohysterography remains unproven and non-integrated into current standards for diagnosing preterm labor; no reliable evidence shows it can accurately detect or predict this condition compared to well-established tools like cervical length evaluation and fetal fibronectin tests. $\boxed{\text{B}}$

